<HEADLINE>
<P>
GIONIS FACES TRIAL WITH SUSPECT IN WAYNE ATTACK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ERIC LICHTBLAU, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Pomona surgeon Thomas A. Gionis will stand trial in the fall along with one of 
the men he allegedly directed to attack ex-wife Aissa Wayne in an attempt to 
gain custody of their daughter, according to two rulings in court Friday. 
</P>
<P>
At his arraignment in Superior Court in Santa Ana, Gionis entered a plea of not 
guilty to charges that he masterminded the Oct. 3 attack. Judge Myron S. Brown 
set an Oct. 31 trial date. 
</P>
<P>
And at a separate hearing, Judge Robert R. Fitzgerald -- over the objections of 
defense attorney F. Lee Bailey -- decided that Gionis should be tried on 
assault charges along with Jerrel L. Hintergardt, 37, of Burbank. 
</P>
<P>
Hintergardt, in custody on $1 million bail, is accused of helping carry out 
last fall's attack on Wayne and financier Roger W. Luby at Luby's Newport Beach 
home. He, too, pleaded not guilty to the charges. 
</P>
<P>
Deputy Dist. Atty. Christopher J. Evans argued that Gionis and Hintergardt 
should be tried together for the sake of legal expediency. "We don't want to 
make the victims and the witnesses go through the same things many times," he 
said in an interview. "We want to do it one time." 
</P>
<P>
But co-defense attorney Allan H.Stokke of Santa Ana said after the judge's 
joint-trial ruling, "We think it's prejudicial that Dr. Gionis is to be tried 
together with a man he's never even met and had nothing to do with." 
</P>
<P>
Bailey, however, played down the importance of the ruling, saying that he 
thought a joint trial would hurt Hintergardt more than it would Gionis. 
</P>
<P>
The nationally known defense attorney also said he is likely to ask that the 
trial be moved out of Orange County to allow his client to get a fair trial 
outside the glare of local publicity. 
</P>
<P>
A second man implicated in the execution of the Wayne-Luby attack, Jeffrey K. 
Bouey, 35, of Simi Valley, has agreed to cooperate with authorities and has not 
yet undergone a preliminary hearing on the charges against him. 
</P>
<P>
Beverly Hills private detective O. Daniel Gal, 32, whom Gionis allegedly paid 
to hire Hintergardt and Bouey and to coordinate the attack, remains in custody 
in Switzerland awaiting extradition. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a judge has agreed to reopen the custody dispute over 2-year-old 
Anastasia that prosecutors say triggered the attack on the daughter of film 
legend John Wayne. The child is in the temporary custody of Wayne, with Gionis 
maintaining monitored visitation rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, F. Lee Bailey makes a point in court Friday as his client, defendant 
Thomas A. Gionis, looks on. DON KELSEN / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
